    <text><body>
            <div type="writingSession">
                <pb n="35r"/>
                <fw type="folNum">1.</fw>
                <opener>
                    <dateline><placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0000407 https://www.geonames.org/2645740">Kew</placeName>
                        <choice>
                            <abbr>Septr.</abbr>
                            <expan>September</expan>
                        </choice> 21<hi rendition="#sup"><hi rendition="#u">st</hi></hi>
                        1854</dateline>
                    <salute>My dear &amp; venerable friend</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I had the great pleasure <lb/>of receiving your most kind <lb/>&amp; flattering
                    letter of last <date when="1854-07" calendar="#gregorian">July</date>,
                    <lb/>through Mr <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0015557 http://d-nb.info/gnd/119074117"><choice>
                        <abbr><subst>
                                <del rendition="#ow">A</del>
                                <add place="across">H</add>
                            </subst>.</abbr>
                        <expan>Hermann</expan>
                    </choice> Schlagintweit</persName>; <lb/>in the middle of <date when="1854-08" calendar="#gregorian">August</date>; &amp; can <lb/>truly say that I have
                    had <lb/>none that gave me so much <lb/>real pleasure &amp; satisfaction
                    <lb/>from the opinion it expresses of <lb/><del rendition="#s">of</del> my <ref xml:id="d016f85f-416c-4548-96f8-5f416ca54807" corresp="#daedd2df-c33c-4f57-add2-dfc33c6f577e" type="editorialNote">Himalayan Journals</ref><note xml:id="daedd2df-c33c-4f57-add2-dfc33c6f577e" corresp="#d016f85f-416c-4548-96f8-5f416ca54807" type="editorial"><bibl corresp="https://edition-humboldt.de/2KMISEKW">Hooker, J.
                                D. 1854.</bibl></note>. I <lb/>have felt so much the influence <lb/>of your career, from my
                    childhood, <lb/>&amp; owe so much to all you have <lb/>done for science
                    generally &amp; for <lb/>myself in particular that I do <lb/>feel it a great
                    privilege to have <lb/>been permitted to write a book <lb/>that has specially
                        interested<pb n="35v"/><fw type="folNum">2</fw>you. Some of my friends have
                    <lb/>too, &amp;<del rendition="#erased">s</del> Mr <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0012148 http://d-nb.info/gnd/118523813">Darwin</persName> &amp; <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0003693 http://d-nb.info/gnd/118674455">Brown</persName> &amp;
                        <lb/><add place="superlinear"><persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H6439677 https://d-nb.info/gnd/116994258">Horner</persName></add> in particular have so constantly <lb/>expressed a
                    hope that my book <lb/>would afford you some little <lb/>gratification that I
                    have <lb/>considered you to be more <lb/>identified with its success than
                    <lb/>any one but my-self. Mr <lb/><persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0012148 http://d-nb.info/gnd/118523813">Darwin</persName> to
                    whom I have shewn <lb/>what you say tells me that <lb/>I may now indeed be proud
                        <lb/>&amp;<del rendition="#erased">s</del> satisfied<supplied cert="high">.</supplied></p>
                <p>And now to answer your <lb/>questions; I am extremely sorry <lb/>for the spelling
                    adopted in <lb/>the map of <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006686 https://www.geonames.org/1269750">India</placeName>, which
                    was <lb/>Mr <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0001901 http://d-nb.info/gnd/119408953">Petermann</persName><supplied cert="high">’</supplied>s doing, he had <lb/>the sheets of letterpress sent him <lb/>as
                    the work proceeded on purpose <lb/>to adopt the same spelling, but<pb n="36r"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">3</fw>did not do so after all. For <lb/>many reasons I should
                    have <lb/>preferred the classical mode <lb/>of spelling, but unfortunately
                    <lb/>it is not prevalent, either in <lb/><placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006686 https://www.geonames.org/1269750">India</placeName> or in <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0005653 https://www.geonames.org/6269131">England</placeName> &amp;
                    the Indian <lb/><choice>
                        <sic>Goverment</sic>
                        <corr>Government</corr>
                    </choice> have taken no <lb/>means of bettering the nomen<g ref="#typoHyphen"/><lb break="no"/>clature, either by suggesting a <lb/>code or following a
                    uniform <lb/>plan themselves.</p>
                <p>With regard to the questions <lb/>you put – 1. I believe that <lb/>as a general
                    rule the Snow <lb/>lies longest &amp; is deepest on the <lb/>north side of each
                    individual <lb/>pass or ridge, when these <lb/>are small &amp; narrow, because
                    <lb/>an ordinary ridge <subst>
                        <del rendition="#ow">l</del>
                        <add place="across">h</add>
                    </subst>owever <lb/>lofty is not so <subst>
                        <del rendition="#s">con</del>
                        <add place="intralinear">important</add>
                    </subst>
                    <lb/>a physical feature amongst the<pb n="36v"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">4</fw>mass of the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006863 https://www.geonames.org/1252558">Himalaya</placeName>, <add place="superlinear">as</add> to <lb/>produce
                    much difference in <lb/>the snow fall, &amp; radiation &amp;c <lb/>of its two
                    opposite slopes: but <lb/>if you regard one of the great <lb/>mountains as a
                    ridge &amp; look <lb/>at its opposite slopes you will <lb/>find the snow fall
                    lower &amp; <lb/>deeper on the <hi rendition="#u">south</hi> flank. <lb/>Thus on
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0020933 https://www.geonames.org/1272390">Donkia</placeName> pass, which is <lb/>a mere
                    ridge of <measure quantity="18500" unit="foot">18500 feet</measure>
                    <lb/>amongst a mass of mountains <lb/>of <measure quantity="20000" unit="foot">20,000</measure>–<measure quantity="25000" unit="foot">25000</measure>,
                    there is snow <lb/>on the North &amp; none on the <lb/>South side. – On
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H5641964">Kinchinjhow</placeName>
                    <lb/>the snow line is at about <measure quantity="16500" unit="foot">16500</measure>
                    <lb/>on the South side &amp; <measure quantity="18500" unit="foot">18500</measure> on the <lb/>north, but on <lb/>the South slope of <add place="superlinear"><placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0000349 https://www.geonames.org/1283259">Kinchinjinga</placeName></add><supplied cert="high">,</supplied> which
                    <lb/>advances far into the wet<pb n="37r"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">5</fw> climate of <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010238 https://www.geonames.org/1256312">Sikkim</placeName><supplied cert="high">,</supplied> the <lb/>snow line is
                        <add place="superlinear">at</add>
                    <measure quantity="16000" unit="foot">16000</measure>, &amp; on the
                        <lb/>North<supplied cert="high">,</supplied> which advances far <lb/>into
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName>, <add place="superlinear">is</add> at <measure quantity="19000" unit="foot">19000 feet</measure>.</p>
                <p>In all these cases the confusion <lb/>arises from the different view <lb/>taken
                    of what is to be called <lb/>North &amp; South slope. If we <lb/>regard that
                    part of the chain <lb/>between the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010714 https://www.geonames.org/1208092">Tsampu</placeName>
                    &amp; Plain <lb/>of <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006686 https://www.geonames.org/1269750">India</placeName> as <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006863 https://www.geonames.org/1252558">Himalaya</placeName>, we may <lb/>confidently say that the
                    Snow <lb/>on the south slope is on the <lb/>average at <measure quantity="16000" unit="foot">16000 feet</measure>, &amp; on <lb/>the north slope at <measure quantity="19000" unit="foot">19000 feet</measure>. <lb/><choice>
                        <orig>t</orig>
                        <reg>T</reg>
                    </choice>hat is to say, that in travelling <lb/>south from the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010714 https://www.geonames.org/1208092">Tsampu</placeName>
                    <add place="superlinear">&amp; ascending</add> you <lb/>will hardly meet with
                    any <lb/>snow below <measure quantity="19000" unit="foot">19000 feet</measure>
                    except <lb/>on the North slopes of ridges that <lb/>rise above that; whereas
                        <del rendition="#s">that</del><pb n="37v"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">6</fw>if you advance North, ascending <lb/>from the Plains of
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006686 https://www.geonames.org/1269750">India</placeName>, you <lb/>will meet <add place="superlinear">with</add> plenty at <measure quantity="16000" unit="foot">16000 <lb/>feet</measure>. It is further to be borne <lb/>in
                    mind that by keeping in <lb/>any of the large river valleys <lb/>you may cross
                    from the Plains <lb/>of <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006686 https://www.geonames.org/1269750">India</placeName> to the
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010714 https://www.geonames.org/1208092">Tsampu</placeName>
                    <lb/>without crossing any snow <lb/>at all – With regard to the <lb/><choice>
                        <abbr>N.W.</abbr>
                        <expan>Northwest</expan>
                    </choice>
                    <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006863 https://www.geonames.org/1252558">Himalaya</placeName>, the chains <lb/>are there so
                    inextricably <lb/>complicated &amp; all of so <lb/>uniform a mean height
                    <lb/>that the amount &amp; duration <lb/>of perpetual snow is pretty
                    <lb/>uniform in most parts <lb/>that are beyond <add place="superlinear">or
                        north of</add> the Southern<pb n="38r"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">7</fw> chains. There is nowhere <lb/>in the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006863 https://www.geonames.org/1252558">Himalaya</placeName> a definite <lb/>uniform <hi rendition="#u">Snow line</hi> such as <lb/>there appears to be on the
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0002454">Andes</placeName>. <lb/>For the breadth of the
                    mass <lb/>is much greater &amp; it is every<g ref="#typoHyphen"/><lb break="no"/>where cut up by meridional <lb/>tortuous valleys.</p>
                <p>I believe that the above is <lb/><persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0016116 http://d-nb.info/gnd/1055397353"><choice>
                            <abbr>Capt</abbr>
                            <expan>Captain</expan>
                        </choice> Strachey</persName>’s view entirely, <lb/>but he does not express
                    <lb/>himself well, he perfectly <lb/>understands the difference <lb/>between the
                    case of a <hi rendition="#u">Pass</hi>
                    <lb/>or small ridge &amp; the whole <lb/>mountain mass, <add place="left">but he
                        does not make this difference clear<choice>
                            <orig>.</orig>
                            <reg/>
                        </choice></add>: <subst>
                        <del rendition="#s">but</del>
                        <add place="intralinear"><subst>
                                <del rendition="#ow">l</del>
                                <add place="across">L</add>
                            </subst>ike</add>
                    </subst>
                    <lb/>the <ref xml:id="f4f1d2fd-aaac-4bfe-b1d2-fdaaac8bfe69" corresp="#e488db9a-bffc-4d83-88db-9abffced83c6" type="editorialNote">Norwegian Alpes</ref><note xml:id="e488db9a-bffc-4d83-88db-9abffced83c6" corresp="#f4f1d2fd-aaac-4bfe-b1d2-fdaaac8bfe69" type="editorial">Vermutlich ist das <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H3631467 https://www.geonames.org/3150042">Skandinavische Gebirge</placeName>, die Skanden, gemeint. Sie
                            wurden früher auch als Skandinavische Alpen bezeichnet.</note>, there is <lb/>no prominent crest or ridge <lb/>to the whole mass, the
                        water<g ref="#typoHyphen"/><lb break="no"/>shed is nowhere a conspicuous<pb n="38v"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">8</fw>feature. 2) The word plateau <lb/>can only be applied to
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName> in <lb/>the sense of a uniformly
                    very <lb/>lofty country – &amp; <subst>
                        <del rendition="#s">that</del>
                        <add place="intralinear">it</add>
                    </subst>
                    <lb/>should always be coupled <lb/>with the words „mountainous“ <lb/>&amp;
                    „rocky“ or rugged. <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H4806588 https://d-nb.info/gnd/1097217914"><choice>
                            <abbr>Capt R</abbr>
                            <expan>Captain Richard</expan>
                        </choice>
                        <lb/>Strachey</persName> who saw <hi rendition="#u">only</hi> that <lb/>part
                    around <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0018705 https://www.geonames.org/1280615">Mansarovar</placeName>
                    <lb/>dwells too much on the level <lb/><subst>
                        <del rendition="#s">no</del>
                        <add place="intralinear">surface</add>
                    </subst> of that part: the <lb/>greater part of the country is <lb/>no doubt as
                    rugged &amp; <lb/>impracticable as possible. <lb/><persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0003944 http://d-nb.info/gnd/117351946">D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi> Thomson</persName> who has seen <lb/>more of
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName> than any one <lb/>considers
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName> even more <lb/>rugged than the
                    Indian <lb/>face of the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006863 https://www.geonames.org/1252558">Himalaya</placeName>, the
                    <lb/>parts I saw were perhaps not <lb/>so rugged as the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006690 https://www.geonames.org/1115007">Indus</placeName> &amp;<pb n="39r"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">9</fw><placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0020681 https://www.geonames.org/1256406">Shayuk</placeName> valleys,
                    but were <lb/>not plains in any sense. <lb/>I do not believe that ⅒<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> or <lb/>1/50 of the surface of <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName> is <lb/>at all to be compared with <lb/>the
                    table land around the <ref xml:id="b6d02072-5dd0-44fd-9020-725dd034fdaf" corresp="#dda2ff91-ff2e-4441-a2ff-91ff2e3441b7" type="editorialNote"><lb/>sacred Lakes</ref><note xml:id="dda2ff91-ff2e-4441-a2ff-91ff2e3441b7" corresp="#b6d02072-5dd0-44fd-9020-725dd034fdaf" type="editorial">Die drei wichtigsten heiligen Seen in <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName> sind <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0018705 https://www.geonames.org/1280615">Manasarovar</placeName>, <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0020611 https://www.geonames.org/1280502">Namtso</placeName> und <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H5574706 https://www.geonames.org/1279634">Yamdrok</placeName>.</note>. Level portions of <lb/>a limited extent occur in all <lb/>parts but they
                    are very seldom <lb/><measure quantity="2" unit="mile">2</measure> – <measure quantity="4" unit="mile">4 miles</measure>
                    <add place="superlinear">wide</add> at the broadest, they <lb/><add place="superlinear">are larger because they border rivers but they</add>
                    <del rendition="#s">&amp;</del> are hemmed in by mountains. <lb/>You may safely
                    say that <lb/>19/20 of <subst>
                        <del rendition="#s"><gap reason="illegible" unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                            <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Thibet</placeName></del>
                        <add place="intralinear"><placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName></add>
                    </subst> is <lb/><ref xml:id="e702512f-a776-4639-8251-2fa776963988" corresp="#f2462094-3d9a-40db-8620-943d9a80db9e" type="editorialNote"><foreign xml:lang="fra">„herissés de Montagnes“</foreign></ref><note xml:id="f2462094-3d9a-40db-8620-943d9a80db9e" corresp="#e702512f-a776-4639-8251-2fa776963988" type="editorial">Herissé de montagnes (frz.): „voller
                            Berge“.</note> – As <lb/>regards the mean height of <lb/><placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName> I do not think it can be <lb/>approximately estimated.
                    <lb/>We may guess the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006690 https://www.geonames.org/1115007">Indus</placeName> at <lb/>its
                    source to be <measure quantity="18000" unit="foot"><subst>
                            <del rendition="#ow">2</del>
                            <add place="across">1</add>
                        </subst>8000</measure> – <measure quantity="20000" unit="foot">20000</measure> &amp; <lb/>at <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010861 https://www.geonames.org/1178338">Gilgit</placeName>
                    <measure quantity="6000" unit="foot">6000</measure><metamark>?</metamark> Also
                    that the <lb/><subst>
                        <del rendition="#s">Br</del>
                        <add place="intralinear"><placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010714 https://www.geonames.org/1208092">Tsampu</placeName></add>
                    </subst> at its source is<pb n="39v"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">10.</fw><measure quantity="18000" unit="foot">18</measure> –
                        <measure quantity="20000" unit="foot">20,000 feet</measure>, at <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H3683728 https://www.geonames.org/1279715">Jigatzi</placeName>
                    <lb/><measure quantity="12000" unit="foot">12000</measure> – <measure quantity="14000" unit="foot">14000</measure><metamark>?</metamark>, at
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0011427 http://www.geonames.org/1280737">Lhassa</placeName>
                    <lb/><measure quantity="10000" unit="foot">10000</measure><metamark>?</metamark>
                    &amp; where the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010714 https://www.geonames.org/1208092">Dihong</placeName>
                    <lb/>enters the wood<subst>
                        <del rendition="#ow">g</del>
                        <add place="across">e</add>
                    </subst>d districts <lb/>of <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0002582 https://www.geonames.org/1278253">Assam</placeName>, i<choice>
                        <orig/>
                        <reg>.</reg>
                    </choice> e. leaves <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName>, <lb/>it is
                    perhaps <measure quantity="7000" unit="foot">7</measure> – <measure quantity="8000" unit="foot">8000 feet</measure>, <lb/>we may also guess that
                    the <lb/>mean height of all the <lb/><hi rendition="#u">watersheds</hi> is <note place="inline" hand="https://edition-humboldt.de/addressee"><measure quantity="2814" unit="toise">2814</measure> – <measure quantity="2970" unit="toise">2970
                            toises</measure></note><measure quantity="18000" unit="foot">18</measure> – <measure quantity="19000" unit="foot">19000 feet</measure>,
                    <lb/>&amp; from these data we may <lb/>compute roughly a mean <lb/>height for
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName>, but it <lb/>will not convey
                    much further <lb/>information.</p>
                <p>Lastly; as to the mean height <lb/>of the Plains <add place="superlinear">or
                        level surfaces</add> that do occur <lb/>in <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName>, I am not aware <lb/>that they affect any particular
                    <lb/>level. That around <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0018705 https://www.geonames.org/1280615">Mansa<g ref="#typoHyphen"/><pb n="40r" break="no"/>
                        <fw type="folNum">11</fw>rowar</placeName>, &amp; which is the <lb/>head of
                    the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0018184 https://www.geonames.org/1115006">Sutlej</placeName> valley, <lb/>slopes gradually
                    down that <lb/>river, from <measure quantity="15500" unit="foot">15500</measure>
                    to <measure quantity="12000" unit="foot">12000</measure>
                    <lb/><hi rendition="#u">I believe</hi><choice>
                        <orig>,</orig>
                        <reg/>
                    </choice> (but speak rather <lb/>at random<choice>
                        <orig>.)</orig>
                        <reg>).</reg>
                    </choice> The loftiest <lb/>part that approaches to a <lb/>level of which we
                    know <lb/>any thing, is probably that <lb/>crossed by <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0004092 http://d-nb.info/gnd/129956252">Turner</persName>, &amp; which, <lb/><del rendition="#s">(</del>though far
                    from <hi rendition="#u">level</hi>, is <lb/>not <hi rendition="#u">rugged</hi><del rendition="#s">)</del>
                    <add place="superlinear">&amp; it</add> must be about <lb/><note place="inline" hand="https://edition-humboldt.de/addressee"><measure quantity="2500" unit="toise">2500</measure> –
                            <measure quantity="2657" unit="toise">2657 <choice>
                                <abbr>t.</abbr>
                                <expan>toises</expan>
                            </choice></measure></note><measure quantity="16000" unit="foot">16</measure> – <measure quantity="17000" unit="foot">17000
                        feet</measure>.<note place="mBottom" hand="https://edition-humboldt.de/addressee"><metamark/>ich
                        ehemals <measure quantity="1800" unit="toise">1800 <choice>
                                <abbr>t.</abbr>
                                <expan>toises</expan>
                            </choice></measure> = <measure quantity="11509" unit="foot">11509
                            feet</measure></note> There are <lb/>probably equally extensive
                    <lb/>level portions at <note place="inline" hand="https://edition-humboldt.de/addressee"><measure quantity="2814" unit="toise">2814</measure></note><measure quantity="18000" unit="foot">18000</measure> to <lb/><note place="inline" hand="https://edition-humboldt.de/addressee"><measure quantity="2970" unit="toise">2970
                            toises</measure></note><measure quantity="19000" unit="foot">19000
                        feet</measure>, <hi rendition="#u">to the North</hi> of <lb/><placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0018705 https://www.geonames.org/1280615">Mansarowar</placeName>, &amp; there are <lb/>flats at
                        <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H3683728 https://www.geonames.org/1279715">Jigatzi</placeName><note place="inline" hand="https://edition-humboldt.de/addressee"><subst>
                            <del rendition="#s"><measure quantity="1857" unit="toise">1857</measure></del>
                            <add place="intralinear"><measure quantity="1875" unit="toise">1875</measure></add>
                        </subst> – <measure quantity="2188" unit="toise">2188
                        toises</measure></note>(<measure quantity="12000" unit="foot">12</measure> –
                        <measure quantity="14000" unit="foot">14000</measure>) <lb/><placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0011427 http://www.geonames.org/1280737">Lhassa</placeName>
                    <note place="inline" hand="https://edition-humboldt.de/addressee"><measure quantity="1563" unit="toise">1563 <choice>
                                <abbr>t</abbr>
                                <expan>toises</expan>
                            </choice></measure></note><measure quantity="10000" unit="foot">10000</measure><metamark>?</metamark> &amp; others I <lb/>believe still
                    lower down<pb n="40v"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">12</fw>the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010714 https://www.geonames.org/1208092">Tsampu</placeName>: there
                    are <lb/>also flats around the <ref xml:id="eff42acb-fcd3-4233-b42a-cbfcd3023383" corresp="#d30aef93-7cfe-4103-8aef-937cfe9103be" type="editorialNote">Salt <lb/>Lakes</ref><note xml:id="d30aef93-7cfe-4103-8aef-937cfe9103be" corresp="#eff42acb-fcd3-4233-b42a-cbfcd3023383" type="editorial">Zu den Salzseen nördlich des <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010714 https://www.geonames.org/1208092">Yarlung Tsangpo</placeName> und von <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H3683728 https://www.geonames.org/1279715">Xigazê</placeName> gehören u.a. der <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0020611 https://www.geonames.org/1280502">Namtso</placeName>, <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H6223956 https://www.geonames.org/1279983">Serling
                                Tsho</placeName> und <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H6085889 https://www.geonames.org/1279916">Tangra
                                Yumco</placeName>.</note>, North of the <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010714 https://www.geonames.org/1208092">Tsampu</placeName>, <lb/>but we
                    know nothing at all <lb/>definitely of 19/20 of <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName>, &amp; <lb/>I believe that 9/10 of the country <lb/><hi rendition="#mMM" hand="https://edition-humboldt.de/addressee">has never been traversed by <lb/>man,
                        being as <choice>
                            <sic>inaccessable</sic>
                            <corr>inaccessible</corr>
                        </choice>
                        <lb/>as the <ref xml:id="b054f7af-77c6-4932-94f7-af77c6993281" corresp="#adcab939-0940-46a1-8ab9-39094026a16e" type="editorialNote">Polar Seas</ref><note xml:id="adcab939-0940-46a1-8ab9-39094026a16e" corresp="#b054f7af-77c6-4932-94f7-af77c6993281" type="editorial">Hiermit ist sowohl der <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0017285 https://www.geonames.org/2960860">Arktische</placeName> als auch der <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0020731 https://www.geonames.org/4036776">Antarktische Ozean</placeName> gemeint.</note></hi> &amp; quite as <lb/>barren. After all I believe that <lb/>the
                    average distance „as the crow <lb/>flies“ performed <subst>
                        <del rendition="#ow">i</del>
                        <add place="across">o</add>
                    </subst>n the routes, <lb/>is the best criterion of the <lb/>amount of level
                    country crossed, <lb/>&amp; we may judge from all our <lb/>materials that so far
                    as this <lb/>is concerned, <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0009370 https://www.geonames.org/1279685">Tibet</placeName> is one of
                    the <lb/>most impracticable countries <lb/>in the world.</p>
                <p>I need not say that I shall be<pb n="41r"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">13</fw>both proud &amp; pleased to <lb/>give you any further
                    information <lb/>in my power.</p>
                <p>I am now almost wholly <lb/>taken up with Botany, chiefly <lb/>Indian &amp;
                    Australian &amp; hope soon <lb/>to commence the distribution of <lb/>the Indian
                    collections of which <lb/>a splendid set goes to <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0005221 https://www.geonames.org/2950159">Berlin</placeName>
                    <lb/>containing every-thing of which<lb/>
                    <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0003944 http://d-nb.info/gnd/117351946">D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi> Thomson</persName> &amp; I
                    have duplicates: <lb/>we are also about to publish<lb/>
                    <subst>
                        <del rendition="#ow">a</del>
                        <add place="across">the</add>
                    </subst> first volume of the <ref xml:id="d7bb5001-f0a4-49d9-bb50-01f0a4d9d9dc" corresp="#bdf06766-cd06-485b-b067-66cd06e85b88" type="editorialNote">Flora <lb/>Indica</ref><note xml:id="bdf06766-cd06-485b-b067-66cd06e85b88" corresp="#d7bb5001-f0a4-49d9-bb50-01f0a4d9d9dc" type="editorial"><bibl corresp="https://edition-humboldt.de/VNWTINB4">Hooker, J.
                                D./Thomson 1855.</bibl></note>, with a very large <lb/>introduct<subst>
                        <del rendition="#ow">ion</del>
                        <add place="across">ory</add>
                    </subst> Essay on the History <lb/>of Indian Botany, Botanical<lb/>&amp;
                    Physical Geography of <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006686 https://www.geonames.org/1269750">India</placeName>, <lb/>&amp;
                    the division of the country <lb/>into Botanical Provinces, &amp; of the
                    <lb/>Flora into its constituent<pb n="41v"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">14</fw>elements. <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0003944 http://d-nb.info/gnd/117351946">D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi> Thomson</persName>
                    <lb/>returns to <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006686 https://www.geonames.org/1269750">India</placeName> in <date when="1855-02" calendar="#gregorian">February</date>
                    <lb/>&amp; takes charge of the <orgName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0020399 https://d-nb.info/gnd/2020025-0">Botanical
                        <lb/>Gardens</orgName> at <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0016218 https://www.geonames.org/1275004">Calcutta</placeName>,
                    thus <lb/>becoming the successor of<lb/><persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0001103 http://d-nb.info/gnd/117598275">Roxburgh</persName>, <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0006224 http://d-nb.info/gnd/117126314">Wallich</persName>, &amp;
                        <add place="intralinear">of</add>
                    <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0020756 http://d-nb.info/gnd/117498246">Falconer</persName>, <lb/>who returns early next year
                    <lb/>to <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0005653 https://www.geonames.org/6269131">England</placeName>.</p>
                <p>My <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0011993 http://d-nb.info/gnd/11698094X">Father</persName> is well &amp; desires <lb/>his
                    affectionate remembrances <lb/>to you; <persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0003693 http://d-nb.info/gnd/118674455">Brown</persName>
                    is in <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0010167 https://www.geonames.org/2638360">Scotland</placeName>, <lb/>&amp; has been there
                    for a month, <lb/>he will not return at present <lb/>I hope, for the cholera has
                    <lb/>been raging at his very <lb/>door in <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0011492 https://www.geonames.org/2643743">London</placeName>.</p>
                <p><persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0012148 http://d-nb.info/gnd/118523813">Darwin</persName> is in <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0000398">Kent</placeName> still &amp; in <lb/>as good health as he ever<pb n="42r"/>
                    <fw type="folNum">15</fw>enjoys, he has just finished <lb/>his <ref xml:id="a9b81660-c09e-44be-b816-60c09eb4be61" corresp="#e0503fed-aa10-4705-903f-edaa10f70568" type="editorialNote">work on Cirrhipedes</ref><note xml:id="e0503fed-aa10-4705-903f-edaa10f70568" corresp="#a9b81660-c09e-44be-b816-60c09eb4be61" type="editorial"><bibl corresp="https://edition-humboldt.de/HTZP7PQT">Darwin
                                1854.</bibl></note>, which <lb/>is one of the best Zoological <lb/>works ever produced in
                    this <lb/>country, &amp; coupled with his <lb/>Journals &amp; Geological works,
                    <lb/>raises him very high indeed <lb/>in European Estimation.</p>
                <p><hi rendition="#u">We all feel the <ref xml:id="aed19008-8bde-4e48-9190-088bde7e486f" corresp="#fc181672-d6c7-4700-9816-72d6c7d700b4" type="editorialNote">departure of <lb/><persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0003776 http://d-nb.info/gnd/118668005">M.
                                Bunsen</persName></ref><note xml:id="fc181672-d6c7-4700-9816-72d6c7d700b4" corresp="#aed19008-8bde-4e48-9190-088bde7e486f" type="editorial"><persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0003776 http://d-nb.info/gnd/118668005">Christian Karl
                                    Josias von Bunsen</persName> war seit <date when="1842" calendar="#gregorian">1842</date> preußischer Gesandter in
                                    <placeName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0011492 https://www.geonames.org/2643743">London</placeName>. <date when="1854" calendar="#gregorian">1854</date> wurde er aufgrund
                                eigenmächtigen Handelns abberufen, was den Abschluss seiner
                                diplomatischen Laufbahn bedeutete.</note> as a national <lb/>loss.</hi></p>
                <closer><salute>Believe me to remain <lb/>with profound respect &amp;
                        esteem<lb/>Your affectionate friend</salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="https://edition-humboldt.de/H0011992 http://d-nb.info/gnd/118774891">JD Hooker</persName>.</signed></closer>
